{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"127b0adc-3767-493c-b6bd-a55a2ac88aa1","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool` on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType` must be `Exe` | Tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### How users install & run it\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nNo other special configuration is needed — stdio transport works naturally since the tool runs as a console process.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c989ec4b-0b5a-49ce-a57f-90d4fe60f0ca","outputTokens":482,"requestId":"F041:126516:11ECBFF:145039F:69F941C6"},"id":"34c37f81-24d0-4e13-9a13-c5faa019c616","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:03:11.770Z","parentId":"d30b9484-f3fe-424e-a7bb-a10e6cae6c8d"}
